MAIN COMPONENTS:
msfconsole - The main command line interface
Modules - exploits, scanners, payloads etc.
Tools - helpful tools that assist with vulnerability research, assessment, or penetration testing. 
Some tools are the following:
msfvenom, pattern_create, and pattern_offset

______________________________________________________________________________________________________________

MODULES:
Auxiliary - scanners, crawlers, fuzzers
Encoders - Allows you to encode the exploit and payload in the hopes that a signature-based antivirus solution may miss them
Evasion - Modules that will attempt to evade detection of antivirus solutions
Exploits - expoits, organised by target system
NOPs - No OPeration, does nothing. Presented in the intel x86 CPU family with 0x90, following which the CPU will do nothing for one cycle. Often used as a buffer to achieve consisten payload sizes
Payloads - Example payloads are; getting a shell, loading a malware or backdoor to the target system, running a command or launching calc.exe as a proof of concept to add to a pen test report.
Having an interactive connection that allows you to type commands that will be executed on the target system.

4 directories under Payloads:
1. Adapters - wraps single payloads to convert them into diffe3rent formats. For example, a single payload could be wrapped in a Powershell adapter, which will make a single powershell command that
will execute the payload
2. Singles - Self contained payloads. Do not need to download an additionals component to run
3. Stagers - Sets up a connection channel between Metasploit and the target system. Good when working with Staged Payloads. Staged Payloads will upload a stager on the target system and then download
the rest of the payload (stage)
4. Stages - Downloaded by the stager. This will allow you to use larger sized payloads.

