WORKING WITH MODULES:

After tnering the context of a module after the "use" command followed by the module name we will need to set parameters.
We can use the "show options" command to list required parameters
All parameters are set using the same command syntax: set PARAMETER_NAME VALUE

PARAMETERS BREAKDOWN:
RHOSTS - Remote host, the IP address of the target system
RPORT - Reote port, the port on the target system the vulnerable application is running on
PAYLOAD - The payload you will use with the exploit
LHOST - Local Host, the attacking machine IP address
LPORT - Local Port, The port we will use for the reverse shell to connect back to. Port on the attacking machine
SESSION - Each connection to target system via Metaploit will have a session ID. We can use this with post-exploitation modules that will connect tot he target system using an exisitng connection

We can use the set command again to change parameters, or use unset to clear a parameter, or unset all to clear all of them.

NAVIGATING MODULES:
1. use exploit/windows/smb/ms17_010_eternalblue
2. setg rhosts 10.10.165.39
3. back
4. use auxiliary/scanner/smb/smb_ms17_010 
5. show options

USING MODULES:
Once we set the parameters we want, we can launch the module using the "exploit" command, or "run"
The exploit command can be used without any parameters or using the "-z" parameter
The "exploit -z" command will run the exploit and background the session as soon as it opens

Some modules support the "check" option to check if the target system is vulnerable without exploiting it.

______________________________________________________________________________________________________________

SESSIONS:
Upon the successful exploitation of a vulnerability, a session will be created.
The communication channel between the target system and Metasploit
We can use the "background" command to background the session
Or CTRL+Z
Use command "sessions" from msfconsole prompt to see the existing sessions

To interact with any session we can use the command "sessions -i" followed by the desired session number
eg. sessions -i 2

